WEBVTT

00:00.543 --> 00:02.682
Sync and corrections by n17t01
www.addic7ed.com

00:04.413 --> 00:06.315
<i>It's Movieland's</i>
<i>biggest night--</i>

00:06.441 --> 00:09.093
<i>a night filled</i>
<i>with unimaginable surprises.</i>

00:09.236 --> 00:12.409
<i>Some will go home winners,</i>
<i>and some will go home losers.</i>

00:12.530 --> 00:13.939
<i>But one thing's for sure.</i>

00:14.062 --> 00:16.379
<i>It's the glitziest,</i>
<i>most glamorous evening</i>

00:16.477 --> 00:17.694
<i>of the year.</i>

00:18.645 --> 00:22.720
Aw. Moths ate my Oscar carpet.

00:22.848 --> 00:23.852
Oh, no.

00:23.947 --> 00:25.462
Where will Brad Pitt walk?

00:25.569 --> 00:27.701
Come on, Mike.
It's exciting.

00:27.816 --> 00:30.371
The Oscars. I like it.

00:30.481 --> 00:31.920
It's a nice bit of escapism.

00:32.014 --> 00:33.724
Yeah, I'm all on board
with escaping.

00:33.828 --> 00:35.811
Well, you're not allowed to.
You're watching it.

00:35.922 --> 00:37.888
It's like the Super Bowl
of Hollywood.

00:38.025 --> 00:39.326
What do you know
about Hollywood?

00:39.431 --> 00:41.204
Hey, I know plenty
about Hollywood.

00:41.294 --> 00:43.656
I do the "People"
crossword puzzle every week.

00:43.781 --> 00:45.561
And 5 across is shut up.

00:45.726 --> 00:48.535
Well, just five more days,
and I'm off to the Windy City.

00:48.678 --> 00:49.918
What are you talking about?

00:50.047 --> 00:51.099
Oh, the Chicago trip.

00:51.217 --> 00:52.706
Every year,
the fifth grade class

00:52.805 --> 00:54.126
gets to take a trip,
and this year

00:54.176 --> 00:55.748
we're going to Chicago
for three days.

00:55.855 --> 00:57.938
They've been having meetings
about it all year.

00:58.106 --> 01:01.253
You... know
I'm in fifth grade, right?

01:01.927 --> 01:04.720
We get to stay in a hotel,
go to museums,

01:04.845 --> 01:06.746
have meals <i>in</i> restaurants.

01:06.843 --> 01:10.479
- Wow. Exciting. That sounds like
quite a trip. - I know, right?

01:10.597 --> 01:11.837
I'm finally gonna see the place

01:11.850 --> 01:14.014
"The Tastes Of Chicago" catalog
is from.

01:17.543 --> 01:18.987
Yeah. He's not goin'.

01:19.992 --> 01:21.508
- What?
- Are you kidding me?

01:21.627 --> 01:24.806
This is Brick we're talking
about. Brick alone in Chicago?

01:24.919 --> 01:27.008
He won't be alone.
He'll be with 30 other kids.

01:27.122 --> 01:30.187
Yeah, for about five seconds
until he wanders onto a bus

01:30.325 --> 01:33.818
or an El train or a boat
or a beam 30 stories

01:33.926 --> 01:36.417
over the city.
Have you not seen "Mr. Magoo"?

01:39.359 --> 01:41.419
- Hi.
- Hi.

01:41.532 --> 01:43.873
Oh, my God.
Did you see how weird that was?

01:44.017 --> 01:46.785
That was so weird.
Wasn't it weird?

01:46.895 --> 01:48.201
So weird.

01:48.507 --> 01:50.097
Okay, I have to tell you
something,

01:50.234 --> 01:52.035
but you have to promise
you won't tell anyone.

01:52.387 --> 01:54.122
Did I tell anyone
when you swallowed a fly?

01:54.223 --> 01:56.625
Okay. Well, when Darrin took me
to the Valentine's Day dance,

01:56.734 --> 01:59.640
and we were cleaning up,
our eyes met over the trash can,

01:59.801 --> 02:01.950
- and he kissed me.
- Aah!

02:02.090 --> 02:04.469
Oh, my God! So are--
are you guys like a thing now?

02:04.607 --> 02:06.435
I don't know. We didn't
really get a chance to talk.

02:06.558 --> 02:07.747
Maybe it was just
the mirror ball.

02:07.856 --> 02:10.794
Whenever there are mirror balls,
people do <i>crazy</i> things.

02:10.920 --> 02:12.200
But what if he really likes me

02:12.316 --> 02:13.721
but he doesn't know
that I like him,

02:13.850 --> 02:16.356
- and that's why he's being so weird?
- That's totally it.

02:16.473 --> 02:17.599
But what if he doesn't
really like me,

02:17.691 --> 02:18.993
and he just got caught up
in the whole romance

02:19.099 --> 02:20.671
of Valentine's Day
and doesn't really know how

02:20.791 --> 02:21.996
to tell me he doesn't like me?

02:22.107 --> 02:23.607
- Well, that makes sense, too.
- Well, which one is it?

02:23.721 --> 02:24.824
- Which one do you think it is?
- What do you think?

02:24.935 --> 02:27.335
- What do <i>you</i> think?
- Oh, my God. I think I really like him.

02:27.479 --> 02:29.030
Unless he doesn't like me back.

02:29.463 --> 02:32.283
Thanks, Carly. You always
give the best advice!

02:35.103 --> 02:36.956
<i>Okay,</i>
<i>so I was pretty darn nervous</i>

02:37.072 --> 02:38.541
<i>about Brick going to Chicago,</i>

02:38.678 --> 02:40.678
<i>but I figured once I heard</i>
<i>the details of the trip,</i>

02:40.732 --> 02:42.003
<i>I would feel better.</i>

02:42.187 --> 02:45.085
<i>I was wrong--
very, very wrong.</i>

02:45.363 --> 02:47.098
Now as far as the hotel goes,

02:47.206 --> 02:48.777
we won't have an adult
in each room,

02:48.904 --> 02:51.890
but the kids will be trusted
to monitor themselves.

02:52.011 --> 02:52.809
Oh, God.

02:52.935 --> 02:55.020
They'll have exactly 26 minutes

02:55.130 --> 02:56.961
to wander
around the Observation Deck

02:57.059 --> 02:59.113
on the 103 floor.

02:59.223 --> 03:00.412
No, no, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

03:00.521 --> 03:02.202
And then it's off
to Gino's East,

03:02.316 --> 03:05.249
where each child will make
their own deep dish pizza

03:05.387 --> 03:07.680
in an 800-degree oven.

03:07.788 --> 03:08.972
What are you doing to me?

03:09.100 --> 03:12.376
And that brings us to 8:25
and the end of my presentation,

03:12.484 --> 03:16.816
right on time as... always.
Thank you.

03:17.028 --> 03:20.435
Okay, uh, very informative,
Mr. Walker.

03:20.560 --> 03:22.967
Now everyone who's interested
in chaperoning,

03:23.093 --> 03:25.975
please put their name
in this bowl.

03:26.084 --> 03:28.117
Remember to fold
your paper squares twice,

03:28.228 --> 03:30.116
once, and once again.

03:30.457 --> 03:31.565
<i>All right, if there was any way</i>

03:31.671 --> 03:33.105
<i>I was letting Brick</i>
<i>go on this trip,</i>

03:33.267 --> 03:34.370
<i>I was gonna</i>
<i>have to do something</i>

03:34.488 --> 03:36.902
<i>that goes against everything</i>
<i>I stand for--</i>

03:37.006 --> 03:38.110
<i>volunteer.</i>

03:38.209 --> 03:40.476
Hi, Connie.
Well, listen, you're in luck.

03:40.593 --> 03:41.676
I've cleared my schedule,

03:41.781 --> 03:43.636
and I'm available
to chaperone the trip,

03:43.742 --> 03:45.804
so Chaperone Frankie
reporting for duty.

03:45.922 --> 03:48.270
Oh, that's wonderful,
Frankie, but actually,

03:48.395 --> 03:50.662
everybody here
wants to chaperone this trip.

03:50.807 --> 03:52.786
This is the crown jewel
of field trips.

03:52.900 --> 03:56.041
Oh. Well, I should really be
one of the chaperones,

03:56.146 --> 03:58.655
'cause I haven't volunteered
for anything all year.

03:58.769 --> 04:00.408
Oh, now do you really think
that's fair

04:00.609 --> 04:02.992
for you to get to go
on the most coveted field trip

04:03.136 --> 04:05.201
after not volunteering
for anything all year?

04:05.304 --> 04:07.694
Look, Brick's kind of special,

04:07.813 --> 04:09.933
and not the kind you slap
a bumper sticker on your car

04:09.979 --> 04:11.911
to brag about, so...

04:12.010 --> 04:14.616
Sorry. We have
a fair way of doing it.

04:14.733 --> 04:16.666
We put all the names
in a big bowl,

04:16.779 --> 04:18.817
and we pick four,
and those are the ones

04:18.950 --> 04:20.149
that get to be the chaperones.

04:20.279 --> 04:21.315
Good luck.

04:26.321 --> 04:27.281
You know, if I were you,

04:27.362 --> 04:28.979
I wouldn't even wanna go
on this trip.

04:29.158 --> 04:32.283
Kids throw up on buses,
and when one goes, they all go.

04:32.403 --> 04:36.530
Okay, here we go.
Fingers crossed, everyone.

04:39.905 --> 04:40.992
"Jenna Bieler."

04:48.075 --> 04:49.404
"Connie McDonald."

04:49.504 --> 04:50.953
Oh, that's me. Oh.

04:55.335 --> 04:56.742
"Julia Laumann."

04:56.845 --> 04:58.370
Whoo!

05:02.014 --> 05:04.361
And finally...

05:07.178 --> 05:08.580
"Scott Ridgeway."

05:09.732 --> 05:11.519
W-wait a minute.
Hold on a second.

05:11.659 --> 05:12.835
A man's name?

05:12.984 --> 05:14.436
How is there a man's name
in there?

05:14.550 --> 05:16.127
I don't see any men here.

05:16.244 --> 05:17.687
He had a previous engagement.

05:17.810 --> 05:20.242
I'm sorry. Something doesn't
smell right here.

05:20.367 --> 05:22.491
I mean, come on. You just
happened to pick your own name?

05:22.601 --> 05:25.665
We're supposed to believe
that was <i>just</i> a coincidence?

05:25.780 --> 05:27.340
This thing is obviously rigged.

05:27.454 --> 05:30.712
I mean, I didn't get picked,
and I put my name in four times.

